\title{Partial Markov categories}
\taxon{doctrine}
\import{macros}

\p{Partial Markov categories generalize both [Markov categories](dct-000I) and
[categories of partial maps](dct-000J) to enable synthetic reasoning about
nondeterministic and/or fallible processes within a single categorical
structure.}

\transclude{thy-000L}

\subtree{
  \title{Partial Markov categories}
  \taxon{definition}
  
  \p{

  A \define{partial Markov category} is a model of the theory of diamond-graded
  monoidal categories in the semantics given by the following square of list
  double monads on \SSet and inclusions between them:

  \quiver{
  % https://q.uiver.app/#
  \begin{tikzcd}[sep=small]
	& {\mathrm{List}_{\mathrm{bij},\mathrm{id}}} \\
	{\mathrm{List}_{\mathrm{inj},\mathrm{id}}} && {\mathrm{List}_{\mathrm{surj},\mathrm{id}}} \\
	& {\mathrm{List}_{\mathrm{fun},\mathrm{id}}}
	\arrow[Rightarrow, from=1-2, to=2-1]
	\arrow[Rightarrow, from=1-2, to=2-3]
	\arrow[Rightarrow, from=2-1, to=3-2]
	\arrow[Rightarrow, from=2-3, to=3-2]
  \end{tikzcd}
  }
  
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{Comparison with the literature}
  \taxon{remark}

  \p{Partial Markov categories have been defined and studied by [Di Lavore et al
  2025](partial-markov-categories-2025). The definition above, like our other
  definitions, differs by making the deterministic and total maps be structure
  rather than properties. It also differs from Di Lavore et al (but agrees with
  Fritz and others) by not assuming at the outset that (partial) Markov
  categories have conditionals.}

}
